{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 1-3.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   What is the subject under discussion as the travelers leave the fourth bridge and reach \softline
the midpoint of the fifth?  Most commentators simply avoid the issue, which probably must remain \softline
moot.  A few offer hypotheses about it, e.g., Benvenuto saying they discussed still other varieties of \softline
divination not touched upon in the examples they had examined (comm. to vv. 1-6), while Trucchi \softline
argues that the two poets are discussing their calumniators and their own good conscience, which \softline
defends them against such as these (comm. to vv. 1-6).  All one may reasonably conjecture is that \softline
the poet had no need to call attention to the subject under discussion if he did not want his reader \softline
to wonder about it.  However, no one has offered anything like a conclusive argument.  And \softline
Davide Conrieri is of the opinion that any such attempt must be considered a flight of critical fancy \softline
("Letture del canto XXI dell'}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Giornale storico della letteratura italiana}{\plain \fs24 \f1  158 [1981], pp. \softline
1-2).  But see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IV.104-105.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Dante's choice of title for his work caused some early commentators difficulty, but not all of \softline
them.  Guido da Pisa (comm. to vv. 1-2), for instance, nearly certainly echoing the Epistle to \softline
Cangrande, says that this work is a comedy because, like other comedies, it begins in misery and \softline
adversity and ends in prosperity and happiness (incipiunt a miseria et adversitate et finiunt in \softline
prosperitatem et felicitatem).  Others see only the stylistic reference of the term, as in the case of \softline
Benvenuto, for whom the title simply means 'my book in the vernacular' (meus liber vulgaris).  But \softline
others, like Francesco da Buti, allow that they are puzzled, wondering whether or not Dante should \softline
so have entitled it, but then allowing that it was his right to do whatever he chose: 'Sarebbe dubbio, \softline
se questo poema dell'autore si dee chiamare comedia o no; ma poi che li piacque chiamarla comedia \softline
debbalisi concedere.  Messer Francesco Petrarca in una sua epistola che comincia: Ne te laudasse \softline
poeniteat ec., muove questa questione e dice: Nec cur comoediam vocet video' (comm. to vv. 1-18) \softline
and see Luca Carlo Rossi, "Presenze di Petrarca in commenti danteschi fra tre e quattrocento," \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aevum}{\plain \fs24 \f1  70 (1996), p. 462, for notice of this passage and its reference to the lost letter of Petrarch.  \softline
For a brief consideration of Dante's sense of tragedy and comedy see the concluding discussion in \softline
the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XX.106-114.  On the question of the 'comic' in these cantos of devilish \softline
playfulness see Bernhard K{\f2\u246\'f6}nig, "Formen und Funktionen grober Komik bei Dante (zu}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1  Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
XXI-XXIII)," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Deutsches Dante-Jahrbuch}{\plain \fs24 \f1  70 (1995), pp. 7-27.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 7-21.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Castelvetro (comm. to vv. 7-15) objects that Dante's wonderfully energetic simile is \softline
almost entirely made up of extraneous elements, i.e., he needed only to say that the pitch in the \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 bolgia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  was as black as that in the arsenal at Venice.  Of course, that is the beauty of it, as Dante \softline
paints his scene as though he had seen the pictures of Breughel before they were painted.  Trucchi \softline
(comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XI.7-18) points out that the 'honest mercantilism' of the Venetians, with all its \softline
vitality, stands against the sordid conniving of barrators.  The pitch, the punishing agent of this \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 bolgia}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , is the apt sign of the nature of barrators (whom we today call 'grafters'), working in secret \softline
and leaving such practitioners enlimed with its sticky sign, attaching to all who practice this kind of \softline
fraud.  'Barratry, the buying and selling of public office, is the civil equivalent of simony, the buying \softline
and selling of church office, the sin punished in the third }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 bolgia}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ' (Singleton, comm. to XXI.38).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Verse 11, 'chi fa suo legno novo,' is understood by nearly all the commentators to refer to \softline
the construction of new ships.  However, the entire context here involves the rebuilding of existent \softline
vessels; thus our translation has it that this phrase refers to making an old ship new.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Verse 16, insisting that what Dante records here is not, as is the aesthetically interesting 
arsenal of Venice, the result of human artisanship, but of God's own and particular craft, which is \softline
merely recorded -- not created (or so the 'official version' has it) by a human agent.  Even the \softline
darkness here is 'miraculous' -- see v. 6 -- as a result of that 'art.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 29.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This figure introduces the 'traditional medieval' devils of plays and festivals to the \softline
poem.  No other scenes in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  are as closely linked to the popular culture of the period as these \softline
in the cantos devoted to barratry.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 34-36.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Benvenuto (comm. to vv. 31-36) suggests that this figure, laden with what \softline
resembles a slaughtered corpse, reminds us of a butcher taking a carcass to be skinned and sold.  \softline
Christopher Kleinhenz has indicated another (and parodic) likely source: Christ as the Good \softline
Shepherd (the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 pastor bonus}{\plain \fs24 \f1  of the Bible and of medieval illustrations), holding a saved lamb on his \softline
shoulder.  See his "Iconographic Parody in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXI," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Res publica litterarum}{\plain \fs24 \f1  5 (1982),  pp. \softline
129-31.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 37.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The name of this class of devils, Malebranche, fits well the place, Malebolge, and \softline
means 'Evil Claws,' referring to their hooked hands, and perhaps to their forked prongs.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 38.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The Elders of Lucca were the city's magistrates, similar in their governance to the \softline
Priors of Florence.  Zita was a young servant woman of the city, dead in the 1270's, to whom were \softline
reputed great kindness and numerous miracles.  While she was not canonized until 1690, she was \softline
reputed a saint shortly after her death, and her cult flourished around her tomb in the church of San \softline
Frediano in Lucca.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab As for the identity of this nameless Lucchese, Guido da Pisa seems to have been the first \softline
commentator to say that he was Martino Bottario (or Bottai).  He seems to have shared political \softline
(and thus grafting) power with Bonturo Dati, mentioned in v. 41 (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXI.41).  There is another \softline
fact about him that is striking: he apparently died, according to Guido (comm. to this verse), on 26 \softline
March 1300, that is, at least in certain calculations, on the very day that is now unfolding in Dante's \softline
poem.  Francesco da Buti confirms his name and also registers the date of his death, now given as \softline
the Friday night before Holy Saturday (but only referring to the month of March, strangely, since \softline
Good Friday fell on 9 April in 1300).  Later commentators, if they refer to this material, all have the \softline
death date as occurring on 9 April, even though this is not authorized by the first commentators to \softline
claim that Martino is the Lucchese here present.  For particulars see Pietro Mazzamuto \softline
(ED.1970.1), pp. 313-14.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 39.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The notion that barrators come straight from earth to this point in hell, carried off by a \softline
devil, seems to violate the rule that all must cross Acheron with Charon (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . III.122-123) and then \softline
go before Minos to be judged (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . V.7-12).  Even the black Cherub who carries off the soul of \softline
Guido da Montefeltro is said (by Guido himself) to have carried him only as far as Minos (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \softline
XXVII.124).  Thus Singleton reasons (comm. to this verse) that the devil at least stops briefly at \softline
Minos's place of judgement in order to allow the formal sentencing to take place.  (Must we also \softline
imagine that he accompanies barrators from Lucca aboard Charon's skiff?)  It is surely true that \softline
Dante is generally precise in honoring the ground-rules that he establishes; it is also true that he has \softline
written a poem, one that allows him to please his fancy when he chooses.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 41-42.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Bonturo Dati, who did not die until 1325, was famed for his barratry.  A popular \softline
tale has it that when Boniface VIII, embacing him at an encounter when Bonturo visited him on an \softline
embassy, shook him, Bonturo said, in return, 'You have just shaken half of Lucca' (meaning to \softline
indicate Martino as the other half).  Dante's devil's exclusion of him from among the Lucchesi who, \softline
suborned by money, will turn an Elder's 'no' into a 'yes' is indubitably ironic and sarcastic: no one in \softline
Lucca is a greater grafter than he.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Tommaseo (comm. to vv. 40-42) points out that Bonturo betrayed Lucca to the Pisans in \softline
1315 and that, therefore, this passage was written before that date or Dante would have consigned \softline
Bonturo to a future posting in Cocytus, among the treacherous.  However, as we must \softline
acknowledge, any such certainty about Dante's choice of the most fit punishment may be tentative \softline
at best.  E.g., why is Dido punished as a lover and not as a suicide?  (See the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . V.61.)\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 46-48.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The ironic edge of the devils' remark is variously interpreted, depending on the \softline
meaning of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 convolto}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  Does this sinner return to the surface with his face now covered with pitch \softline
(in which case he resembles the ebony face of Christ on the much-venerated image of the \softline
Crucifixion in San Martino, in Lucca)? or is he bent in two, emerging with his backside from the \softline
pitch (in which case he looks like a citizen of Lucca kneeling to prostrate himself before the \softline
image)?  Strong arguments are made for each interpretation, and each is supported by a further text \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXII. 25-28; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXII.19-24), in which the sinners in this }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 bolgia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  are compared, second to \softline
frogs with only their snouts out of water, first to dolphins showing their backs as they move \softline
through water.  Either meaning is completely possible, but most contemporary commentators prefer \softline
the latter, perhaps because it is the more burlesque.\par
