{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Nonetheless, it remains interesting that Barbi (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Problemi di critica dantesca}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Florence: \softline
Sansoni, 1934]), p. 273, supports reading }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 convolto}{\plain \fs24 \f1  as 'covered up in' with the example of a text in \softline
Bono Giamboni (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Orosio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , V.xix): 'Mario fuggendo... nelle paludi di Minturnese si nascose; della \softline
quali malavventuratamente }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 del fango tutto convolto}{\plain \fs24 \f1  tratto....'  See also Isidoro Del Lungo (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dal \softline
seculo e dal poema di Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , vol. II [Bologna: Zanichelli, 1898]), pp. 471-72, offering the \softline
following equivalences for the word: 'involto, ravviluppato, ravvolto, in materia sporca o \softline
appiccicosa.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 49.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The Serchio is the river near Lucca in which citizens swam for refreshment in the days \softline
of summer.  That the devils address Martino would tend to support the notion that it is his head that \softline
has surfaced rather than his rump, i.e., they would seem to be saying 'Man, that's no way to do your \softline
imitation of the Holy Visage!'  Guido da Pisa thinks of a passage in the Bible (Deut. 32:20) in ways \softline
that might make his reader consider a parodic intent, if Dante were also thinking of it: 'Abscondam \softline
faciem meam ab eis' (And I shall hide my face from them).  The Mosaic text speaks, of course, of \softline
God's hiding his face from humankind.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 58-62.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil's self-assurance will shortly be proven to have been ill-founded.  Here begins \softline
the longest episode in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ; it will run through Canto XXIII.57, some 290 verses.  See \softline
Hollander, "Virgil and Dante as Mind-Readers (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXI and XXIII)," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Medioevo romanzo}{\plain \fs24 \f1  9 \softline
(1984), pp. 85-86.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 63.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Some Renaissance commentators (e.g., Vellutello [comm. to vv. 61-63] and Daniello \softline
[comm. to vv. 58-63]) insist on the proximity of the word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 baratta}{\plain \fs24 \f1  to barratry, which would indicate 
that the word is likely to indicate a previous scuffle with these very demons -- who certainly seem \softline
the types to have bothered Virgil on his descent to Cocytus when Erichtho sent him on his mission \softline
down there (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IX.22-27).  The first commentator in the DDP to try a different tack is Singleton \softline
(comm. to this verse): 'Virgil may be referring to his difficulties with the devils at the walls of Dis \softline
(see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VIII.82-130) or to some skirmish that he had with these devils on his previous journey to \softline
lower hell (see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IX.22-30).  The first meaning seems more probable and\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 more significant, since Virgil appears to forget that his difficulties before Dis were solved not by \softline
himself but by a messenger from Heaven.  Hence Virgil here exhibits the same self-confidence he \softline
showed in the earlier encounter, before the devils shut the gate in his face.'  The fact that Virgil is \softline
shortly to be found out of his depth in his struggle with the Malebranche, again after exhibiting self-confidence in the face of hostile demons, strongly supports this reading.  It does not invalidate the \softline
understanding that Virgil has earlier had a set-to with these very demons, but may stand alongside \softline
it.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 67-72.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil's calm assurance is shredded by the attack of the 'dogs' who rush out upon \softline
him, a poor beggar.  The simile is hard on poor Virgil, who only barely manages to regain control of \softline
the situation, which, we remember, is being observed by Dante, squatting in hiding on the bridge.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 76-78.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The entry on the scene of Malacoda ('Eviltail'), the lead devil of the Malebranche of \softline
Malebolge, is perfectly in character, as we shall see.  He pretends to be servile, but mutters under \softline
his breath about his sense of Virgil's futility.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 79-84.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil's aplomb, his 'high style' contrasting with demonic 'vernacular,' serves at once \softline
to set him apart from the 'low-life' devils and their leader, Malacoda, but also to make him seem \softline
slightly ridiculous, since Malacoda, not he, is eventually in control of the situation, as Virgil will \softline
only finally realize, to his considerable chagrin, in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXIII.140-141.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Does Virgil remember Malacoda from his last visit?  Or has he only repeated Malacoda's \softline
name because he has just now heard it from the other devils?  The plural 'your' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 vostri}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ) seems to be \softline
generalized and to refer to all and any demonic opposition that he and Dante have encountered so \softline
far in their journey, actually only once before, at the gates of Dis (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VIII.115-120).  Virgil's \softline
phrasing at v. 82, combining references to the will of God and to the (pagan?) Fates, picks up his \softline
identical coupling of these two powers in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  IX.94-97.  A Christian guide might have only \softline
used the first term. (Guido da Pisa, in his gloss to this passage, refers explicitly to the different \softline
ambiences of the two expressions, the first being 'theological,' the second, 'pagan' [comm. to vv. 79-82]).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Virgil's reference in verse 83 to the fact that he is not alone ('Let }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 us}{\plain \fs24 \f1  proceed') for the first \softline
time alerts Malacoda and his cohort to Dante's hidden presence.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 85-87.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Malacoda's fearful gesture, letting fall his billhook, is a masterful ploy that succeeds \softline
in getting Virgil to lower his guard.  See Sam Guyler, "Virgil the Hypocrite -- Almost: A Re-interpretation of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXIII," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  90 (1972), p. 34.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 88-93.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil, tricked, orders Dante to leave his hiding-place.  The devils, sensing fresh \softline
meat, crowd forward.  Dante's fear is a more realistic response to the situation than is Virgil's self-assurance.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \ul0 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 95.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Dante was present at the successful siege of Caprona in 1289, a cavalryman observing \softline
the success of the mission of his Tuscan Guelphs against this Pisan stronghold.  It is to his lasting \softline
credit that what he remembers for us is how the victims must have felt when they came out under a \softline
pact of safe-conduct.  Dante, exiled on the charge of barratry by his fellow citizens, here perhaps \softline
means to remind them that he had borne arms on behalf of the republic in its victories, the siege of \softline
Caprona in August of 1289, and the previous great victory at Campaldino that June, referred to \softline
later in this scene (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXII.4-5).  He was not a grafter, scheming in the dark, but a cavalryman \softline
who did his deeds in the fearsome clarity of war.  There have been several attempts in the last two \softline
centuries to relate the scenes and personnages of these cantos of barratry to Dante's own \softline
experiences as accused barrator perfidiously sent into exile on this pretext (and thus presented as \softline
attacked by the twelve Priors of Florence, the Malebranche), and to his military experiences, offered \softline
as vindication against such malicious and untrue charges.  For cautionary remarks, urging restraint \softline
in such interpretation, see Conrieri ("Letture del canto XXI dell'}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Giornale storico della \softline
letteratura italiana}{\plain \fs24 \f1  158 [1981]), pp. 38-39.  For perhaps the first attempt to claim that Dante had \softline
constructed a developed autobiographical 'political allegory' in this scene, see Rossetti{\u8219\'27}s \softline
introduction to his commentary on }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXI.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 100-105.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Dante's fears are justified; only Malacoda's intervention prevents the bullying \softline
devils from assaulting him with their hooks.  Malacoda holds back Scarmiglione, encouraging him \softline
to await a more propitious moment for his attack.  Scarmiglione is the first of the ten devils to be \softline
named.  He is apparently not included in the squad of ten put under Barbariccia's control -- see the \softline
note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXI.118-123.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 106-111.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Malacoda's partial truth (the sixth bridge, over the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 bolgia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  of hypocrisy, is in ruins) \softline
is quickly joined to a total lie (the next bridge along their route is intact).  }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 All}{\plain \fs24 \f1  the bridges are down, \softline
as Virgil will be told by Fra Catalano in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXIII.133-138.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 112-114.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This extraordinarily precise time reference is the most certain text in the poem for \softline
establishing an external date for the journey.  It is 7am of Holy Saturday, since Christ, according to \softline
Dante (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Conv}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IV.xxiii.10), died at noon.  In fact Dante here is modifying the facts, if on the \softline
authority of Luke (Luke 23:44), who gives the time of the preternatural darkness as noon.  Even \softline
Luke, however, is clear that Jesus died at 3pm.  Dante is willing to rewrite any text to suit his \softline
purpose.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab From this passage we learn that the events narrated in this poem occurred in Easter week of \softline
1300.  However, and as we have seen, Dante seems to be conflating two dates for the start of the \softline
journey, each of which is propitious, 25 March and 8 April (the actual date of Good Friday in 1300) \softline
in order to gain the maximum significant referentiality.  See the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.1.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 115-117.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Malacoda lies yet again, promising safe-conduct.  Once again Virgil is trusting, \softline
Dante not.  \par
